segments.text: Mr. Barber by Scott Burnham.

On the 26th of November at Mr. Barber's house concerning the Vietnam War, in the interest of accumulating knowledge about the war, I'm going to donate this tape to the Texas A&M Oral History Collection in the University Archives.
Is this all right with you?
Yes.
First of all, I'd like to get a little biographical data, such as where and when you were born and some of your background education.
Okay.
I was born in Orange, New Jersey.
On October 4th, 1929, my father was an engineer for the New York Telephone Company.
I went to school in public schools in New York through my junior year in high school.
And after World War II, shortly after World War II, my parents bought a farm in New Hampshire.
And I went to school my senior year up there and then went to the University of New Hampshire.
Graduated in 1951 with a degree in economics.
I was also an ROTC graduate.
Okay, and so when did you just come straight out of ROTC and join the military?
Yes, I went straight out of the university into the Air Force and then into pilot training in 1951.
Okay, and can you briefly explain your military career before Vietnam?
Okay.
I finished pilot training in 1953 and went straight to Korea and was there for the last five months of the war.
Then the unit moved to Japan, was there for about nine months, came back to the United States and spent about ten years in fighter units in the United States and Europe.
I was a combat crew for Tactical Air Command, the Strategic Air Command, and the United States Air Forces in Europe.
After about eight years, I got into the accident investigation business and I did that in addition to crew duty for about three years.
There was a lot of work involved with that.
I didn't particularly like it.
Those accident investigations took about 30 days, and some years we'd have 12, 13 accidents in the unit.
I found very little time for my family.
I decided to go to night school, which I did.
I took a bunch of math courses and applied for a special program.
with the Air Force Institute of Technology.
I went to Texas Tech for two years under an Air Force program.
Got a degree in industrial engineering.
Then when I got out of school, the Cuban Missile Crisis was still upon us.
I went back into the F4 program and for a couple of years at MacDill in Florida.
Went to Europe, worked in safety education.

for a couple years, went to Spain, did staff work for 16th Air Force, the Mediterranean Command there in Spain, then went to Korea, or excuse me, went to Vietnam for a year in Edwards Air Force Base for a year and retired in 1971.
Okay.
About your involvement in Vietnam, as a fighter pilot, what sort of background knowledge did you have of Vietnam
as far as our involvement there?
Well, I had spent, of course, three years in Europe and immediately before my tour in Vietnam.
And what we were exposed to over there was the Armed Forces Radio Network, the Stars and Stripes newspaper.
Of course, we got periodicals like Time and so forth.
But the majority of our news and what we got came from the armed forces press.
So I didn't know much about the country.
I was pretty well up to speed on the war itself because, of course, I was interested in it.
And I worked with people who had been to Vietnam, who had come back.
And I felt like I was aware of the conflict, the reasons for it.
but as far as the culture and so forth about Vietnam, I hadn't studied.
Okay.
Where and when were you stationed in Vietnam and what types of planes did you fly there?
I was stationed at Da Nang Air Base from August of 69 to August of 70 and it was all F-4 fire bomber work during that year.
Okay.

In bombing, what were your objectives and targets, as well as we learned a lot about the restricted zones, about how for one month this zone you could bomb there and then you couldn't because of the politics of it.
What are your thoughts on that, and what were some of your objectives and targets?
Well, first of all, our targets were very specific.
We would go to a briefing.
We were given a target folder, and they said, this is your target for today.
This was most of my involvement.
I didn't sit much of the strip alert business.
I had a full-time job in addition to my flying duties.
So, I avoided sitting out there for like some of them did for six or eight hours and you might get you might get flushed out and go someplace and you might not depending on how the war was going.
So, we would go, we would have specific targets assigned.
We would

almost invariably worked with a forward air controller in a light aircraft who was controlling the strike and he would he would mark the target or close to it with a rocket or a phosphorus rocket and so we were you know I guess there probably were restricted zones where you could go in and out out of
But that was far above us as far as we were the operators and that really didn't mean much to us.
We went to the target that they gave us.
We had primarily, we were after storage areas, enemy supply storage areas.
The Ho Chi Minh Trail was, I would say, probably 80% of our work.
suspected troop concentrations, barracks and so forth.
Most of the time you couldn't see what you were going after because of the jungle.
We'd go after road cuts once in a while, roads on the sides of hills, mountains.
We laid mines on rivers, roads.
We escorted reconnaissance aircraft into North Vietnam.
We escorted B-52, well we flew air cover for the B-52s every once in a while.
They weren't operating in North Vietnam very much while I was there.
We had some radar drops where we would be controlled by radar and we'd go in just like the B-52s did.
We occasionally go after
a gun emplacement or some specific target that somebody would divert us to.
Were these areas mostly north of the DMZ or were they in South Vietnam?
Most of our work was out of country work.
It was in Laos, Cambodia and some in North Vietnam.
What kind of bombs did you drop?
We learned about the smart bombs and all the new technology they had.
We didn't have many.
I think that most of the smart bombs went to specialized units.
As far as I know, we didn't have any.
I don't know anybody that dropped any.
I don't recall seeing any.
But we had conventional bombs.
The Mark 82s, I think they were 750 and 500 pound bombs.
most of the time with regular fuses, sometimes with fuse extenders.
We dropped quite a few CBUs, the cluster bombs, that would come open at, I think, 1,500, 2,500 feet, and they would scatter out a circle of bomblets 1,500 feet or so.
Some of them were instantaneous.
Some of them were delayed timing.
Did you ever encounter a resistance?
You said you flew with the A-52s and stuff.
What type of resistance did you normally find?
Mostly aircraft, light anti-aircraft fire.
We didn't see any heavy anti-aircraft, the black smoke ones.
They would, most of the time, they wouldn't bother you until you were down on a bomb run, and then they'd shoot at you.
there was a lot of ground fire and you really didn't appreciate it in the daytime because you didn't see it.
You would see the puffs from the anti-aircraft.
At night, on the night missions, you would see an awful lot of ground fire in some areas.
Amazing amount of fire that was coming up out of the countryside.
Was it a viable effort?
Was it a main concern of yours?
Would it be a possibility of being shut down by these?
You're pretty well aware of the odds.
It was always in your mind, just like having an automobile accident is in your mind.
you knew pretty well what the history of the outfit was, and you found out right away how many people had been lost, how many aircraft they'd lost, and so forth.
So we didn't really have a big loss rate.
I probably maybe lost, out of the three squadrons there, we might have lost one crew a month.
Maybe 2% of the people weren't going to make it.
Another 10% were probably going to have accidents.
Accidents were a lot bigger problem than the combat losses were.
And I felt that there were some accidents that were probably rated as combat losses that really weren't.
Okay, back to the bombing aspect.
What effect do you think the bombing had on the enemy as far as the psychology of the enemy or their will to fight?
I think that it probably had a very significant effect on them.
I know the North Vietnamese, from what I've read since I came back, were extremely afraid of the B-52 attacks.
And they were certainly something.
You've probably seen films of that.
They would lay a stream of 500-pound bombs from here to Highway 71.
a mile or so of them, just complete devastation.
And, of course, we weren't that devastating to them, but we carried as many bombs on an F-4 as a B-17 did during World War II.
So we could, you know, we'd hang around for, we'd be on the target for 15 minutes probably while we made a number of runs.
And I think that, of course, we were on the receiving end of some of the aircraft
fire too.
They'd rocket the base every once in a while and that has a psychological effect on everybody.
You know, your chance of getting hit are kind of like a lightning strike, but just the same, it's unnerving.
Now, what we did to them day after day and along the trail there, I don't mean just the Air Force, the Marines and the Navy and everybody else was over there and it was
tremendous effort, and I think that it probably had a very significant effect on their morale and their ability to do things.
Okay, as far as the fighter pilots, did you ever like assist ground troops?
Were you ever called in?
No, you know that the in-country work in South Vietnam, for example, the Marines had
at Chu Lai flew all their missions in country and I imagine they did a lot of ground support.
The only direct ground support mission that I was involved in was over in Cambodia.
I think it was the first day that we went into Cambodia.
We had been dropping what was called hard ordnance, conventional bombs and so forth.
And all of a sudden, we switched to what they called soft ordnance.
They were bombs that were dropped from low level.
They had special fins on them that came out kind of like an inverted flower petal when you dropped the bomb.
And that would slow them down and you could drop them further.
I don't know, 1,500 feet or something.
Most of that stuff we were dropping from, I don't know, 7,000 or 8,000 feet probably.
But on that particular mission, there was a group of houses and some friendlies over in a tree line that we were told about, and we were told to take out one of those houses.
Were these...
The troops that you were assisting, were they U.S. troops?
I assume so.
I assume they were U.S. because that was mostly a U.S. operation.

The Vietnamese were sneaking across the border into Cambodia and using it as a sanctuary and then they'd come in, hit and run, and go back over there and I guess it was President Nixon who decided that we'd go in there and clean them out.
I don't think they did.
I think they left before we got there.
You said that a large percentage of your job in Vietnam was more of a staff officer or other duties.
Could you kind of briefly describe some of those duties?
Well, I was the chief of safety for the wing there at Da Nang.
Da Nang Air Base, half the base was, one side of the base was Air Force, the other side was Marines.
the Chief of Safety for the Air Force side.
Primarily my job was to advise and assist the commander there in the accident prevention business.
So we did a number of things.
We would investigate accidents and incidents.
We would respond to all kinds of problems and questions.
I had about eight people working for me.
They did a lot of inspections.
We would assist other inspectors when they came in.
Air Force people were in there regularly, so were the Pacific Air Force people and 7th Air Force.
Everybody and his dog came over there to see what was going on, and we'd escort them around.
We had a safety council.
a wing-based safety council once a month and that generated a lot of activity for us.
We pretty near stayed busy doing all the homework we got out of that meeting getting ready for the next one.
We've dealt with careerism as a problem in the services there.
Did you observe any examples of careerism at the expense of the war effort?
I don't think at the expense of the war effort.
Sometimes that's difficult to interpret, but I can remember individuals that I thought put their self-interest in front of other people's.
I remember one guy who flew
a large number of escort missions into North Vietnam, escorting the reconnaissance aircraft.
And really, those were nothing missions.
Your job was to go along with the reconnaissance airplanes.
They were low-level missions.
And if anybody shot at them, why, we were to retaliate against whoever shot at them.
Well, they never got shot at.
And at least, you know, during that time period, they didn't.
So, all it was was kind of a dry run operation.
The hooker to the thing was that missions into North Vietnam counted twice as much for awards and decorations as missions in Laos, which really wasn't right.
Laos should have counted four times as much as North Vietnam, but at that time,
because the shooting was off for the majority of my tour.
There was a time period there when they did go back in on the north, but I'm talking about most of the time, and especially on those reconnaissance missions.
But that type of thing was something that I didn't respect the guy for.
I thought it was crappy of him, but you see that type of thing in any career.
Opportunist is going to jump on it and try and make the most of it.
Also, another aspect of the war was the one-year tour duties, which seemed to not really give the officers in particular a chance.
In the first three months, they'd be getting used to it, and then they'd only have four months while they were there, and then the last time they'd be packing up.
What did you think of the one-year tour duties?
Did you think it was a good idea?
Well, they had to balance out the other requirements all over the
all over the world with what was going on in Vietnam and I thought that the one-year tour was appropriate.
If you wanted to stay, you could.
I could have stayed if I wanted to.
And a lot of people did.
People came home, they went back but there were
No, you were away from your family for a year, like I left a wife and five kids and went over there and stayed for a year.
I thought it was a fair amount of duty time.
You worked seven days a week, and it was an awful grind, really, as far as the workload went.
So I really didn't have any argument with the one-year tour.
Okay.
There was another concept of
the idea of getting your ticket punched, as they used to say.

We talked to this one guy that was in the Air Force Academy, and everybody that was there was saying, well, get over to Vietnam now, go get your ticket punched, because it's the only way you'll ever become a general or you'll ever rise up in the ranks.
Did you ever see any people just coming over to maybe getting a soft job just to put Vietnam on the resume?
No, I don't think so, because...
You never could tell what kind of job you were going to get when you got there.
You might be shipped over as one thing and wind up as something completely different.
So there was no doubt about it that if you wanted to advance in the military, anybody in the military, you better get that kind of duty behind you.
And it was important to everybody's career, but
you know, if you're being in the military, that's what you're there for.
It's kind of like being a fireman.
You don't go to the fires, there's no sense in being in the fire department.
So, you know, I realize that some people felt, may have felt that way, but I didn't.
I certainly, I was anxious to go because it was something that
was part of your job and I was very surprised when I got sent from Florida to Europe for three years because the war was on when I was in Florida.
We were sending units out of MacDill to Southeast Asia for 90 days or something like that in rotating duty and the word was that nobody was going to go any place but Southeast Asia.
When I got my orders to Europe I was very surprised
and disappointed because I figured what would happen would be I would spend three years in Europe and then go to Southeast Asia, which is exactly what happened.
It was kind of an ass-backwards way to do things.
Okay.
In dealing with Arvin at the South Vietnamese troops, did you have to deal with Arvin fighter pilots or was it strictly U.S.?
Well, we had the Vietnamese on the base with us and we were kind of co-mingled with them.
they would have an operations building right next to ours.
At least they did at one time and on the flight line they had their helicopter area and their bombs stashed all over the place.
We were always kind of leery of them because it was kind of, it appeared to be kind of loosey goosey but they, we really didn't have much to do with the Vietnamese.
There was one Vietnamese captain
who we saw quite a bit of.
He was their flight safety officer.
And he would come down and talk to us about various problems every once in a while, or he'd want something.
He was a pretty good guy.
He'd been through the flight safety officer's course at the University of Southern California.
The main obstacle with the Vietnamese was language.
Their language is impossible.
And one of the smartest people I ever knew couldn't master it.
I didn't even try, and I don't know anybody that smoked even a
you know, more than a few words of Vietnamese.
And we were not allowed to socialize with the Vietnamese officers.
So, we never went to their houses, they never came to our parties, we didn't go to theirs.
It was completely, you know, separate but equal type operation.
What do you think about that?
Do you think it would have been a better idea to try and maybe be a little bit more involved?
I guess, but you know, I think there were too many obstacles to it.
One thing, you never know.
There was so much enemy activity around, so many people that, you know, the guy would be the gardener during the day and at night he'd be out firing the rockets into the base.
And the same with the house girl and all that.
You never knew who to trust because of the guerrilla type operations that they did.
And I don't understand why
You know, the ban was on the fraternization business.
I suspect partly was because of the terrorist activities.
Maybe they'd had some real bad experiences with that.
It may have been over the women, I don't know what it was all about, but
It just, they didn't seem particularly anxious to do it either.
They kind of left us alone, and we left them alone.
That's my experience on one air base.
It may have been different.
I know people that lived with the Vietnamese.
There's a guy in our office who was in Special Forces.
He was out in the communities, you know, in the Jones.
As far as the missions, where they originated from,
Was there any South Vietnamese input?
Did they say, well, we think you had a bomb here?
I think that there was at a very high level.
I think the Vietnamese had to say something about what we went after in country.
But of course, that wasn't our concern.
We were out of country work most of it.
So I don't think they had much to say about that.
They may have.
They could care less what we did over there.
What we were trying to do was shut off the supply that's coming down the Ho Chi Minh Trail.
And they should have been thrilled that we were doing that.
Do you ever think that there was a sense of ingratitude amongst the South Vietnamese?
No, I don't think so.
The South Vietnamese, to me, just didn't appear very motivated about the whole damn thing.
They seemed to me, I suspected they were politicians.
I thought that they were probably on the order of Ferdinand Marcos in the Philippines.
Probably on the take, probably half crooked.
We probably put them in there, the ones that were there when I was there.

and that just didn't seem to be too fired up about the war, but then again, I didn't, that's just a casual observance, because I didn't really have any real contact with the South Vietnamese officers, except this one guy.
Okay, starting with the war in general, kind of on a big scale, did you feel the war was winnable at the time you were there, or do you,
How would you describe a winnable situation given that country?
Well, I think the United States could have won the war if we had wanted to, if we had been turned loose.
I think with enough conventional forces, we could have taken over South Vietnam.
Now, I'm not so sure we could have kept it, but we could have won it.
It would have been a real tough go because the Vietnamese
the VC and the North Vietnamese probably would have been right back in there.

They were very innovative and clever and good guerrilla fighters and I think that they would have pulled a, they would have gotten back, we might have thrown them out, but I think they'd have come back in.
They, we could have won it with, we could have won it by going into North Vietnam and that probably

would have been with nuclear weapons and that would have certainly could have been done, but I think it would have opened up a scenario for a much bigger war and we'd have had other countries involved.
Russia or China?
The country wasn't prepared for that.
The United States never would have supported that.
The politicians knew it, and that's why we fought the limited war that we did.
So you mentioned that we were held back.
Who was holding us back?
Was it Congress or was it the President?
Well, I think basically it was the American people, and they were sending messages to the Congress, and the Congress was listening.
And the press, of course, was against the war and probably will be against every war that we ever fight.
That's just the nature of our liberal press, but there was no real support for the war like there was.
I was a teenager in World War II and I remember the support that everybody gave to the war effort.
There wasn't 10% of that in the Vietnam War.
People just wanted it over with.
They didn't want to see Americans over there
dying and they didn't want to see their money spent on it and it was, you know, a losing cause almost from the beginning because there was no support.
Who do you think you can blame for not having support?
I mean, obviously, you know, during the World War II era, you know, the government had a lot to do with drumming up support.
Do you think it was a fact that just the government was trying to fight this war and
you know, just say, well, it's over there, don't worry about it?
We didn't see the threat.
The American people didn't see a threat from that.
You know, it was the falling domino theory that, you know, Thailand would go, Cambodia would go, Vietnam or in the opposite order, and pretty soon, you know, we'd have them on our doorstep.
Well, and that was, that part of the world was necessary to our national interests, we were led to believe.
And I think to a certain extent that's true.
The American people didn't perceive that as a real threat.
Now they saw Hitler as a real threat.
And they saw the Japanese as a real threat.
Actually, the United States just sat around and was a good neighbor to Great Britain until the Japanese bomb.
Pearl Harbor, and as the Japanese general said, we've awakened the sleeping giant.
Well, nobody awakened us in Vietnam.
We just, you know, we kind of muddled our way through, and there was no big cause to get us moving as a country.
Also, some of the problems we've heard more later on in the war, in the 70s, late 70s, was the problem with drugs.
I think it was more with the marine grunts and the actual fighting people, but did you ever encounter any problems with drugs?
No, really I was kind of naive as far as the drug problem went.
The Air Force, you know, it's a little different deal because
We had people in a very controlled environment on an air base.
You had all volunteers.
By and large, you have people who are probably better educated.
They're high school graduates, or at least.
And they're working with pretty sophisticated equipment.
There wasn't as big an awareness of the drug problem at that time.
It was 20 years ago.
I did see it one time.
We got called out in the middle of the night and some guy had gotten hit by an airplane out on the runway.
It was a Marine.
They were of course on the other side.
We had the Air Vietnam terminal on our side of the base and had a fried chicken place in it.
And these guys had crossed the field, crossed the airfield, rather than go around the end of the runway, which probably would have been a five mile hike either way.
They came directly across, which was maybe a mile, mile and a half.
We're crossing the runway and an airplane landed and it hit one of them.
The wing hit this guy in the head and killed him dead.

And I went down to the, the Air Police had his buddy and they had him held down in their security office and they were waiting for the Marines to come pick him up and I went and talked to him and it was obvious he was just as stoned as you could possibly be.
He was completely out of it.

I mean, fixed air and just, you know, would hardly communicate and everything and they were blasted out of their minds on something and so, you know, that kind of woke me up a little bit to the drug problem, but I didn't see any evidence and I was in a position where I would have known had we, had they
had a problem with drugs on the base.
I worked closely with the people who were in charge of the whole thing and they just, you know, there wasn't any.
If it was there, we sure as hell didn't know about it.
So on the base, I mean it was more like, did you ever stray from the base or was it just pretty much like you had your own community there?
We had our own community.
I got off the base
I can only think of one time.
I think we went out to some communications facility that was a few miles off the base.
We had to go through town and we stopped by and saw that China Beach operation.
You've probably seen it on TV.
The beach where the Marines came ashore.
But going into town was not encouraged.
In fact, I can't remember being restricted to base, but we probably were.
There was no real need to go to town.
We had what we needed on base and that really wasn't an attractive place to be.
Concerning, we also dealt with the inter-service rivalries.
which I guess goes on since the creation of all three services, but to what extent did you see that in Vietnam in the effort there?
Well, I didn't see any inter-service rivalry.
Of course, we had nothing to do with the Army at all.
The Army was off there in the jungle someplace and we just didn't have anything to do with it.
There weren't any Army people on the base.
If there were, there were one or two.
The Marines, of course, were very much in evidence.
As far as the work that had to be done, we didn't have any problems with the Marines.
We had a job to do.
Really, it was not much of a joint effort as far as the Marines.
The runaways were kind of a joint operation and some of the problems on the airfield.
For the most part, the Air Force was the host base though.
Host service on the base.
The Marines, really I lost a lot of respect for the Marines there.
I thought they were a well-disciplined outfit and I found out that they couldn't even get their enlisted men to salute over there.
It was that bad.
I had a Marine officer in there.
We were in their club one night having some drinks and one of these Marine lieutenant colonels took it upon himself to get

hacked off about something, some little thing, and he stood up and gave me the bird in the middle of this club, which I went over and talked to him and promptly left with the people that I had come in with.
We got out of there, but it was a nasty scene.
He called me up the next day and apologized, but I think somebody told him to do it, but I just, you know, I was kind of surprised at their behavior.
But as far as rivalry, you're right, that goes on.
It's kind of like neighbors, competitiveness in the office and at school and every other place.
Each one is trying to get their piece of the pie, but it wasn't a problem over there as far as the war went, I thought.
A lot of talk about some of the secret campaigns like Nixon's wars and a lot of the CIA stuff that went on.
One in particular was the Air America.
Were you aware of that?
I knew about Air America and I think it's generally recognized that Air America is the CIA's Air Force.
I thought that they were kind of glorified freight haulers really.

They hauled all kinds of stuff all over the place and they made a lot of money and they were mercenaries as far as I was concerned and I respected them for what they did but I thought they were kind of overrated.
They got a lot of press that I knew
people that flew for them.
When I was there they were, they'd drift in and out.
But they were for the most part, they weren't really in the heavy duty stuff.
I'm sure they got shot at a lot because they flew, what they flew and where they flew.
But as far as the secret wars, I think that we did what was right for the times.
President Nixon had
had his hands full with that war and he wasn't the one that really got us into the thing big time.
But there were, he had to fight the press and everybody else and try and get done what needed to be done.
I don't think
that there were any secrets from the people in Congress or the Senate.
I don't think there are any secrets in Washington about military affairs.
Those guys get briefed and they let their buddies know and they let whoever know they think is going to do their bidding for them.
They try to keep a lot of things quiet.
There again, it was a different time.
I think it was in the best interest of the country at the time.
People's lives were at stake and they were trying to achieve certain objectives and the secrecy was part of it.
That probably hurt some congressional feelings, but that was part of the game.
Were you aware of any of the CIA bases in Cambodia or Laos?
I wasn't aware of any.
I'm sure they have, but it wasn't hard.
They probably wouldn't tell us about it.
We had no need to know.
You mentioned earlier that you respected the enemy troops.
Yeah.
What were your thoughts about the war?
I had a lot of respect for the North Vietnamese regulars.
I thought they were very well disciplined.
They could get along on nothing.
They put up with a lot of hardships and really they fought a good war against the French and against us.
And some of the things they did, you know, the United States figured that the war was pretty near won in 1968.
and we were being told that.
The American public was being told that and then all of a sudden the Tet Offensive came about and it was pretty clear that we didn't have control of that place at all.
That the North Vietnamese and the Viet Cong could do a hell of a lot of damage if they wanted to and they did.
And really that was the turning point of the whole thing.
a lot of politicians that had supported the war, all of a sudden decided, hey, you know, we're not going any place in this thing.
We better get out.
The VC, I didn't have as much respect for.
Certainly they were clever and they were good fighters, but really they were kind of rabble gorillas as far as I was concerned.
But you gotta give them credit.
Between them and the North Vietnamese, they won the thing.
Okay, concerning anti-war efforts and stuff, how did you feel specifically about the anti-war demonstrators and their efforts?
Well, I suspected the motives of a lot of the war demonstrators.
I thought a lot of that stuff that originated on the campuses was probably self-serving for a lot of people on the campuses that didn't want to go over there, didn't want to fight.
So, they're out protesting and raising hell and running down the war effort and everything for
probably largely personal reasons.
A lot of them took off and went to Canada and that appalled me.
I thought they should have been shot for that.
But one of our presidents, I forgot who it was, decided that they should all be pardoned and let the bastards back in.
But it makes me wonder what's going to happen in any future war.
Does everybody decide then whether they want to go fight it or not?
I seriously
wonder if we can fight any war without some real changes in attitudes.
But I think that the protesters had a real significant effect on the war effort.
Of course the press was against the war anyway.
Then the protests came along and they kind of played up to the press.
The press gave them a lot of coverage and
I think it helps sway a lot of people who were on the fence or who may have even been for the effort back the other way.
We had people like Jane Fonda who went up to North Vietnam and consorted with the enemy while people were dying a few hundred miles away for what was supposed to be our national interest.
I respect their right to demonstrate.
I think, you know, that's part of our country.
Certainly, the violent demonstrations, the draft dodgers and all the rest of it, I thought was too far.
Certainly, it was too far and it was tolerated because
the war wasn't popular and they got away with things that I think set a bad precedent.
I'm not so sure that they could get away with it in any kind of a war that was anywhere near supported by the American people, but they did because nobody cared.
What about the veterans that would come back and join like the Vietnam veterans against the war and the veterans for peace?
What did you, what did you feel about it?
Well, I feel sorry for those people.
I think they're kind of pathetic.
I think a lot of them were probably misfits in the service and they came back home and they couldn't fit in in civilian life.
and they go off and became professional complainers and whiners and so forth.

Instead of putting that behind them, getting on with their lives and what had to be done, supporting their families and so forth, why, you still see them running around in all that hippie military stuff that they wear.
And I think they give the whole Vietnam era
and the veterans a bad public image and I wish that they would go get some jobs and forget about it.
You know, it's behind us, something in history.
Did you see any, as far as like in the service in Vietnam, any anti-war feelings or anti-war demonstrations or
I mean, even within the service, was there a bad feeling about it?

No, you know, as far as my remembrance was, you know, of course there were people who weren't too thrilled about going over to Vietnam, but that was personal reasons and but as far as anti-war feelings and so forth, I couldn't detect any at all.
Most of the people in the Air Force in particular
You know, it was just another job.
We had a whole string of jobs to do over the years, and that was another.
